        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@i-d-lytvynenko, I reproduced this on Windows 10 version 1809 (build 17763.737) and inspected the output stream from `conhost.exe`:\n```shell\n# case:\necho foo^Gbar\n\n# win11\n\\r\\n\\x07\\x1b[?25lfoobar\\x1b[5;1HD:\\\\a\\\\neovim\\\\neovim>\\x1b[?25h\n\n# win10 1809\n\\x1b[?25l\\x1b[H \\x1b[3;1H\\x1b[?25h\\x1b[?25lfoobar\\x1b[14X\\x1b[14C\\r\\n\\x1b[20X\\x1b[20C\\r\\nD:\\\\a\\\\neovim\\\\neovim> \\x08\\x1b[?25h\n```\nAs you can see, `conhost.exe` does not emit the `BEL`(`\\x07`) to nvim, so aside from upgrading Windows, there doesn't seem to be a viable workaround. :)\n\nFYI, nvim's terminal on Windows relies on [Pseudoconsole](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/console/pseudoconsoles), which was introduced in version 1809 and was not fully mature at the time.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-05T10:04:16Z",
